My key insight is this: instead of treating narrative graphs as static structures derived post-hoc, we should model them as *causally intervened* dynamic systems, where splits are designed not only to prevent leakage but also to *stress-test* whether models rely on genuine understanding or spurious narrative correlations. This leads to a new framework: **Counterfactual Narrative Splitting (CNS)**, which integrates counterfactual data augmentation with causally grounded train/test isolation. CNS actively generates counterfactual versions of narratives (e.g., same claim, different entity; same event, different temporal framing) and uses them to both *construct* and *evaluate* splits. By ensuring that counterfactual variants are placed in opposite sets (one in train, one in test), we force models to generalize beyond surface-level narrative patterns. This goes beyond buffering by *engineering* generalization pressure directly into the split design. It also enables direct measurement of a model’s sensitivity to narrative manipulation—an interpretable metric of robustness.

